      {
        "id": 4161482,
        "name": "Robert Grenley",
        "username": "Robert_Grenley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/robert_grenley/{size}/977_2.png",
        "created_at": "2023-09-26T04:12:16.949Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I noted that no wines were tasted between 1992 and 2017, which would encompass the years when B du M became particularly and excessively (in my experience) prone to premature oxidation in roughly \u201895-96, and the later vintages when Premox may not yet have reared its ugly head. Since you note that they adhere to a regimen of natural cork, do we have any idea whether we feel that they have taken any measures to hopefully assure that the pox is behind them, or whether they still may not be a producer\u2019s wine that can be safely and appropriately aged?</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 7,
        "updated_at": "2023-09-26T04:12:16.949Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
